 ## --text--

-What is a potential drawback of overusing currying in your code?
+Which of the following is an example of a curried function in JavaScript?

 ## --answers--

-It always makes the code run slower.
+```js
+function add(a, b, c) {
+  return a + b + c;
+}
+```

 ### --feedback--

-Remember what we mentioned about the readability of heavily curried code.
+This is a regular function that takes all parameters at once.

 ---

-It can make the code harder to read.
+```js
+function add(a) {
+  return function (b) {
+    return function (c) {
+      return a + b + c;
+    };
+  };
+}
+```

 ---

-It reduces the reusability of functions.
+```js
+function add(a, b, c) {
+  return a() + b() + c();
+}
+```

 ### --feedback--

-Remember what we mentioned about the readability of heavily curried code.
+This function accepts all parameters at once and calls them like functions, which does not follow the definition of a curried function.

 ---

-It increases memory usage significantly.
+```js
+function add(a) {
+  function inner(b) {
+    return a + b;
+  }
+}
+```

 ### --feedback--

-Remember what we mentioned about the readability of heavily curried code.
+The inner function is never returned, so `add(2)` will return `undefined` and `add(2)(3)` will throw an error.

